column12:
This picture caught my attention because of the political signs, “Oakland Stands United Against Hate” and “March for Our Lives”
For me personally, signs like these touch my heart because I feel that it is important to stand together in the Bay Area against racism and discrimination, as it has become more evident with the recent political climate. I was born and raised in the Bay Area and it makes me proud when people stand for what is right.

column10: The photo shows a residence with a portable outhouse positioned in the front yard, and a sign to beware of dogs. I did not hear any dogs or any people nearby. The house may be under construction, but I conducted my observation on a Sunday and there were no workers to be seen. I was unable to ascertain if the building was abandoned or only undergoing renovations. It may be worth noting that when I went to match my photo with a street address on Google Earth, the image shown on the latter depicted that this house was once in much better repair.
column11: This photo shows what was probably a multiple family residence, surrounded on all sides by high, vision-blocking fencing. At first glance, I assumed from the fencing the building was abandoned, but when I looked closer, I saw lights on and a campaign sign in the window. Flowers grew behind the fence, and the yard appeared to be somewhat maintained. It may be worth noting that when I returned to google earth to match my images to their addresses that the fence was not shown.
column12: This photo is of the street corner directly outside of the house pictured in image 2, showing the large waste items left on the corner. There are a few large items of furniture, denoting the possibility of recent moving or vacating of the residences nearby.

I was struck by the severe disrepair of the front landscaping for the house pictured, versus the house next door, which was well-kept and decorated for Halloween. Again, the recurring juxtaposition of well kept homes existing directly next to severely dilapidated ones was striking.

column10: This is one of the modern homes on the block. The front has a very modern and clean aesthetic and it is well kept. This home was the only house on this block with this type of style home. The rest of the homes on this block were also smaller and this home stood out to me.
column11: This is an example of the apartment complexes on my block. The front area has vegetation and is maintained well with no garbage. The car in the front of the house is a Subaru, suggesting that these individuals can afford a good car.
column12: This was the corner house on my residential block. There is no garbage or debris in the front of the house.  Also, the front lawn has roses, plants and a hose, suggesting that the occupants of this house take the time to garden.

column10: My thoughts about this image was that the city made considerable efforts to maintain biking lanes and upkeep traffic control in regards to these lanes. This makes me think that the city puts an emphasis on more ecological means of transportation. They city is also likely able to do this because they have the funds for it, and considering that there are several markets, schools, and convenience stores in this residential area, everything residence need is within biking distance, which is probably why the city (as well as its residents who are involved in city management and likely want to use/advocate for these biking lanes) cares to even do this. Unfortunately, I do not see this often in poorer communities.
column11: In terms of image 2, we see this street sign is not like any other. It is made from stone with the street name engraved at the top under a statue of a sphere. This work of art, especially just for a street sign, is not common among impoverished neighborhoods, where street signs may not even be present. This street sign is symbolic of the wealth of the city and its citizens, denoting that they have the capital to build such an aesthetic monument for such an "average" object.
column12: Across the street is a gas station, near the hub of the city. Unless most other gas stations in impoverished neighborhoods, this gas station is very well kept, not always super busy, and has seen some renovations in the past (I know because I used to stop there when I was younger). The business is obviously investing money into this specific station, likely to please their affluent customers/maintain the image of the area. The price of gas is fairly high.
column13: Next to the Public Library, there is a park consisting of a big grass field and trees. The area looks very well maintained (Thick bright green grass and green flourishing trees) as apposed to parks I have seen in the inner city that are mostly dirt and dark green weeds. I saw many children who seemed to be a part of the after school program playing in the park with some adults. I could tell the staff and volunteers are very involved in the programs, and that the library is thriving. The park, as well as the surrounding area, was clean of all trash, even loose leaves.
column14: One of the biggest observations to be made was of the housing. The houses were significantly well kept, in terms of the house itself and the gardening/driveways. These houses probably go for $700,000 and up. You could tell it was a wealthy community. I didn't see much people, but the area was only somewhat diverse.

column10: The street was actually pretty nice, no potholes or roughness. The lawns and areas around the block were also very neat yet in front of one house on the block, There was a huge pile of garbage. While I know what garbage can implicate as it is mentioned in the survey. It can imply a lack of ability or want to care usually within a poorer society- but this seems more like an anomaly like a garbage person dropping part of the house’s garbage without realizing.
column11: My main point in taking this specific photo is what it shows about the neighborhood, it is clearly a youth’s bike whether young 20s or a middle schooler. However, the importance comes with how the person left the bike. The bike was chained to the post with a fancier chain than the ordinary $5 one from Walmart which indicated a certain amount of wealth. The helmet was simply clipped to the side and things were left in the basket which implies a certain amount of trust in the area. I never saw the owner come back for her bike and even otherwise I wouldn’t be able to guess if she was a resident nearby. However, the bike itself was very indicative.
column12: This is a photo of the picture painted on the side of the bowling alley and while it was not on my block face, it was very clearly visible standing on the block face and looking across the street to the Bowling Alley on San Pablo, I found it interesting the statement that the owners and potentially the area is trying to make with the emphasis of “ since 2003”. A lot of areas strive for character and something personal and establishments that have been around for awhile tend to accomplish that. My city back home has a movie theater that has been around since the 20s, what it attempts to do is to take the current commercialization and add nostalgia which has economic and class implications in a comericalized, developed area.

column10: I thought this movie theater was an interesting addition to the neighborhood. It is not a regular movie theater—all of the showings were of movies I have never heard of before. They were indie films that came out of the Sundance Film Festival. I thought the style of this cinema added to the expensive/wealthy aura of the neighborhood, because indie movies are an acquired taste for people who have seen them before.
column11: I found this little shop really interesting because a cashew creamery is not a very common finding. I have personally never seen one before, and eating non-dairy/vegan, artisanal, made-in-shop foods is an expensive habit. Again, this adds to the wealthy aura of the neighborhood.
column12: Many of the houses had signs such as these standing in front of the house, which indicate their political preferences/leanings. The members of this community are not afraid to voice their political opinion, either because they feel safe in the environment because their neighbors have the same opinions or they are strong-willed and determine people. However, it seems to be the first case because most of the signs are for more liberal causes.

column10: In most of the houses on my block, there were signs that conveyed a political message or that of social activism. It was really interesting because I have never seen so many signs concentrated in one area. There were 7 signs that I recorded, exactly like the one in the picture. Others found included, March for Our Lives, Resist Fear, Love is Love, and Defend Life.
column11: As mentioned in my fieldwork notes, there were certain areas of my block that had very modern and new houses such as the one in the picture. It was interesting to see how it contrasted with the other houses that were smaller and less renovated. This observation/scene also made me realize that the houses in general are very compact and close to each other.
column12: I think this particular sign is important because of the bottom line where it says “We look out for each other!” I have seen neighborhood watch signs like such in other neighborhoods, including my own, but they never have that quote on them. This one does, and it was the first thing I noticed. This is significant for the neighborhood itself, as it represents how the community is and how they interact/rely on one another.
